<!-- ================ Usage ================================ -->
<sect1 id="cpufreq-applet-usage"> 
   <title>Usage</title>
   <para>When there is no cpufreq support in the system, the &applet; only displays the current CPU frequency.</para>
   <para>When cpufreq is supported in the system, the &applet; displays the CPU icon with a progress bar. The state of the progress bar represents the current CPU frequency with respect to the maximum frequency.</para>
   <para>By default the &applet; display the current CPU frequency, but you can configure it to display it as percentage instead, or even to display only the icon. For more information on how to configure &applet; see <xref linkend="cpufreq-applet-prefs"/>.</para>
   <para>Each instance of &applet; can monitor only one CPU. You must start an instance of &applet; for each CPU that you want to monitor if you are in a multiprocessor system (SMP).</para>
   
   <sect2 id="gnome-cpufreq-selector">
      <title>Frequency Selector</title>
      <para>To set the CPU frequency, click on the applet, then a menu will be shown with the list of available frequencies in your system. Now simply choose the frequency you want to set.</para>
      <figure id="cpufreq-applet-selector-img">
	 <title>&applet; Frequency Selector</title>
	 <screenshot>
	    <mediaobject>
	       <imageobject>
		  <imagedata fileref="figures/cpufreq-applet-selector.png" format="PNG"/>
	       </imageobject>
	    </mediaobject>
	 </screenshot>
      </figure>
      <warning><para>If the frequencies menu is not shown, please ask to your system administrator.</para></warning>
   </sect2>

</sect1>

